Hatchbacks 2016-2017: The Best and the Rest
The following are the winners of our Editors' Choice award for the best hatchback cars of 2016 and 2017. We view these vehicles as the best hatchbacks, best compact hatchbacks, and the best sport compact hatchbacks you can buy today.
Editors' Choice*
City Cars

    Chevrolet Spark
    MSRP: $13,535 - $18,160
    EPA: 31 city/39 hwy
    Overview: The Spark’s persona is less shocking than its name, but those seeking basic urban transportation will be happy.
    Fiat 500
    MSRP: $17,990 - $25,490
    EPA: 31 (Est) city/40 (Est) hwy
    Overview: Retro styling and a cheerful character make the 500 a fashionable choice among city cars.
    Mitsubishi Mirage
    MSRP: $13,830 - $17,330
    EPA: 33 city/41 hwy
    Overview: This basic five-door transportation comes with a good warranty and a maximum fuel-economy rating of 43-mpg highway.
    Smart Fortwo
    MSRP: $15,400 - $19,230
    EPA: 32 city/39 hwy
    Overview: The charming and nonconformist Fortwo’s mission is to make motoring easy for urban dwellers with its maneuverability and compact shape.

Compacts

    Honda Civic
    MSRP: $19,475 - $27,335
    EPA: 27 city/40 hwy
    Overview: The Civic, offered as a sedan or a coupe, exemplifies automotive excellence and underscores Honda’s commitment to blending fun with efficiency and practicality.
    Mazda Mazda 3
    MSRP: $18,680 - $27,330
    EPA: 29 city/41 hwy
    Overview: Not many vehicles successfully combine style, dynamics, and value in a compact package—the Mazda 3 does.
    Volkswagen Golf
    MSRP: $19,315 - $28,245
    EPA: 25 city/37 hwy
    Overview: The Golf is one of our favorite cars—it’s so good, we named it to our 10Best list for 2016.
    Chevrolet Cruze
    MSRP: $16,995 - $25,245
    EPA: 28 city/39 hwy
    Overview: Not as razor sharp as some of its more enthusiastic competitors, the Cruze offers the ride of a bigger car in a compact package.
    Ford Focus
    MSRP: $18,100 - $24,600
    EPA: 26 city/36 hwy
    Overview: A European-developed chassis gives even the base Focus a rare blend of agility and accuracy, making it enjoyable to drive even when compared with newer competitors.
    Hyundai Elantra
    MSRP: $18,085 - $22,535
    EPA: 26 city/36 hwy
    Overview: The handsome Elantra has balanced proportions and angular sheetmetal, and it also offers great value.
    Hyundai Veloster
    MSRP: $18,835 - $24,785
    EPA: 27 city/35 hwy
    Overview: The Veloster is a pseudo hot-hatch—its quirky styling stands out in traffic—yet its racy looks deceive.
    Kia Forte
    MSRP: $16,840 - $22,840
    EPA: 29 city/38 hwy
    Overview: More than just a budget box, the Forte offers lots of features at a pocket-pleasing price.
    Mini Cooper Hardtop
    MSRP: $21,550 - $22,550
    EPA: 28 (Est) city/39 (Est) hwy
    Overview: With a sporty and robust chassis, the spunky Cooper Hardtop provides tossable handling; the upscale cabin makes it a comfortable cruiser.
    Scion iM
    MSRP: $19,255 - $19,995
    EPA: 27 city/36 hwy
    Overview: The iM is versatile, affordable, and hardly a down-market consolation prize thanks to a slew of standard features and lots of accessories.
    Subaru Impreza
    MSRP: $19,090 - $24,390
    EPA: 25 city/34 hwy
    Overview: Sensible, spacious, and trustworthy—these traits make the Impreza a safe choice, but not an exciting one.
    Toyota Corolla iM
    MSRP: $19,615 - $20,355
    EPA: TBD
    Overview: Scion’s demise is the Toyota showroom’s gain, as the iM becomes the Corolla iM for 2017.

Electric Vehicles

    Chevrolet Spark EV
    MSRP: $25,995 - $26,385
    EPA: 128 city/109 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: The Spark EV dials in some much needed fun by improving just about everything wrong with its gas-powered counterpart.
    Kia Soul EV
    MSRP: $32,800 - $36,800
    EPA: N/A
    Overview: The funky Soul EV appeals to the eco-friendly, keeps the utility of the gas-powered Soul, and adds a host of tech features to please even the geekiest hamsters.
    Volkswagen e-Golf
    MSRP: $29,815 - $36,415
    EPA: 126 city/105 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: Sporting most of the excellence of its gasoline-powered counterpart, the e-Golf zaps its way into a growing field of affordable electrics.
    Chevrolet Bolt EV
    MSRP: $37,500
    EPA: TBD
    Overview: Quick on its feet and fun to toss around, the Bolt EV is an affordable and enjoyable electric car worth waiting for.
    Fiat 500E
    MSRP: $32,795
    EPA: 122 city/108 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: With its tiny size, zippy handling, and an EPA range of 87 miles, the 500E is a fine city car—as long as you don’t need to go anywhere else.
    Ford Focus Electric
    MSRP: $30,045
    EPA: 110 city/99 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: You might miss the exhaust note, but otherwise the Focus Electric is very similar to its gasoline-powered sibling.
    Mitsubishi i-MiEV
    MSRP: $23,845
    EPA: 126 city/99 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: No, it’s not a larger-than-life computer mouse; it’s the i-MiEV, the least-expensive EV sold.
    Nissan Leaf
    MSRP: $29,860 - $37,640
    EPA: 124 city/101 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: The Leaf’s earth-friendly image, relaxed ride, and spacious cabin make it an affordable EV with everyday usability.
    Smart Fortwo Electric Drive
    MSRP: $25,750
    EPA: 122 city/93 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: The Smart Fortwo ED should be the most logical and painless of the EV conversions, but we have tested it and found it lacking.
    Toyota Mirai
    MSRP: $58,365
    EPA: 67 city/67 hwy
    Overview: In Japanese, “mirai” means “future,” and the Mirai is the future of motoring: It runs solely on hydrogen and its only emissions are water.

Entry-luxury Cars

    BMW 3-series
    MSRP: $34,145 - $50,195
    EPA: 23 city/35 hwy
    Overview: At one time, the 3-series was the benchmark for all sports sedans, but its once uncompromised tactility has been slightly softened in this latest generation.

Entry-luxury Electric Vehicles

    BMW i3
    MSRP: $43,395 - $47,245
    EPA: 127 city/107 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: With its carbon-fiber/aluminum structure and electric powertrain, the i3 advances BMW’s legendary driving dynamics into the future.
    Mercedes-Benz B-class Electric Drive
    MSRP: $42,375
    EPA: 85 city/83 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: The B-class puts some juice into the legendary three-pointed star, making for a truly electrifying experience.

Exotic Sports Cars

    Ferrari GTC4Lusso
    MSRP: N/A
    EPA: N/A
    Overview: In a category full of two-seat supercar coupes, the GTC4Lusso politely requests a table for four.

Hybrid Vehicles

    Chevrolet Volt
    MSRP: $33,995 - $38,345
    EPA: 53 city/45 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: Despite the Volt’s eco image, it’s actually fun to drive, without the range anxiety of pure electric vehicles.
    Audi A3 Sportback e-tron
    MSRP: $38,825
    EPA: 86 city/86 hwy (MPGe)
    Overview: A pleasing blend of hybrid and hatchback, the A3 e-tron gives you Audi cachet and power, plus an EPA-rated 83–86 MPGe.
    Ford C-Max
    MSRP: $25,045 - $32,645
    EPA: 42 city/37 hwy
    Overview: While comfortable and fun to drive, the C-Max’s high EPA-estimated fuel-economy numbers are basically fantasy.
    Honda CR-Z
    MSRP: $21,130 - $25,925
    EPA: 31 city/38 hwy
    Overview: The CR-Z is an ambitious attempt at making a sporty hybrid, but its performance doesn’t match its adventurous styling.
    Lexus CT
    MSRP: $32,225
    EPA: 43 city/40 hwy
    Overview: If you’re into the relentless pursuit of fuel efficiency—but you can’t take the doorstop style of the Toyota Prius—the CT200h may be what you seek.
    Toyota Prius
    MSRP: $25,065 - $30,865
    EPA: 54 city/50 hwy
    Overview: With its combination of space and efficiency, the Prius is quite compelling—in our experience, 50 mpg is achievable, even at near-80-mph speeds.
    Toyota Prius C
    MSRP: $20,425 - $25,360
    EPA: 53 (Est) city/46 (Est) hwy
    Overview: Take the uninspired underpinnings of the Toyota Yaris and mix with it an even less powerful version of the Prius hybrid powertrain and you get the Prius C.
    Toyota Prius V
    MSRP: $27,540 - $31,800
    EPA: 44 city/40 hwy
    Overview: Blending the usefulness of a station wagon and the fuel economy of a hybrid, the Prius V might be the ultimate utility vehicle.

Luxury Four-Door Coupes

    Porsche Panamera
    MSRP: $79,150 - $264,950
    EPA: 18 city/28 hwy
    Overview: As with the Cayenne SUV, the wildly successful Panamera has proven that the Porsche 911’s mystique translates to four doors.

Mid-size Luxury Cars

    BMW 5-series
    MSRP: $51,195 - $73,495
    EPA: 23 city/34 hwy
    Overview: Once upon a time, the 5-series was a tactile, agile hot rod for the autobahn; today, not so much.

Performance Four-door Coupes

    Porsche Panamera Turbo / Turbo S
    MSRP: $142,350 - $201,550
    EPA: 15 city/24 hwy
    Overview: There’s 520 hp and 516 lb-ft of torque coming from a twin-turbo V-8, making the Panamera Turbo equal parts supercar and luxury chariot.

Premium Sport Compacts

    Audi RS3
    MSRP: TBD
    EPA: TBD
    Overview: The RS3 is cram-packed full of Audi’s high-performance gear, but in a tidy package—expect it here in 2017.

Small Crossovers and SUVs

    Jeep Compass
    MSRP: $20,690 - $26,990
    EPA: 23 city/30 hwy
    Overview: Ruggedly handsome and clearly utilitarian, the Compass tries to channel its Jeep forebears but is far from an off-roader.

Sport Compacts

    Ford Fiesta ST
    MSRP: $22,335
    EPA: 26 city/33 hwy
    Overview: As its name implies, the Fiesta ST, with a mighty turbocharged engine and sport-tuned suspension, is hot, spicy, and ready to party.
    Volkswagen Golf GTI
    MSRP: $25,815 - $33,550
    EPA: 25 (Est) city/34 (Est) hwy
    Overview: The Golf GTI is the progenitor of the hot-hatch genre, and age has not dulled its abilities.
    Volkswagen Golf R
    MSRP: $36,470 - $39,815
    EPA: 22 (Est) city/31 (Est) hwy
    Overview: If you love the GTI but crave more power, check out the Golf R—it’s also a 10Best winner for 2016.
    Fiat 500 / 500C Abarth
    MSRP: $23,570 - $27,690
    EPA: 28 (Est) city/34 (Est) hwy
    Overview: The tiny 500 goes from pipsqueak to bad-ass as the hot-rod Abarth, the heart of which is a raucous 160-hp turbocharged four-cylinder.
    Ford Focus RS
    MSRP: $36,775
    EPA: 19 (Est) city/25 (Est) hwy
    Overview: Rally-driver wannabes and hot-hatch hooligans, your wait is over: The Focus RS is here.
    Ford Focus ST
    MSRP: $25,300
    EPA: 22 city/31 hwy
    Overview: The Focus ST belongs on any enthusiast’s short list, combining a high fun-to-drive factor with the every-day versatility of a four-door hatchback.
    Mini Cooper Hardtop S / JCW
    MSRP: $24,950 - $31,450
    EPA: 23 (Est) city/33 (Est) hwy
    Overview: Quirky styling and nimble handling help the Cooper S to inject a dose of excitement into your daily commute.

Station Wagons

    Fiat 500L
    MSRP: $20,490 - $25,790
    EPA: 22 city/30 hwy
    Overview: The 500L features styling that’s adorable to many but a bit too squee-worthy to others.
    Mini Cooper Clubman S / JCW
    MSRP: $28,500
    EPA: 23 (Est) city/33 (Est) hwy
    Overview: Sports-car athleticism and cheeky styling are hallmarks of the Mini brand; cargo space isn’t, so here’s the Clubman S with up to 48 cubic feet of storage.

Subcompact Crossovers

    Kia Soul
    MSRP: $16,750 - $22,150
    EPA: 24 city/30 hwy
    Overview: Perhaps overshadowed by its eye-catching exterior, the Soul’s solid build quality and smart interior are the real deal.

Subcompacts

    Ford Fiesta
    MSRP: $15,455 - $19,705
    EPA: 28 city/36 hwy
    Overview: Though the Fiesta might be small, it is still mighty fierce.
    Honda Fit
    MSRP: $16,725 - $22,000
    EPA: 29 (Est) city/36 (Est) hwy
    Overview: A flexible interior, an efficient powertrain, and agreeable pricing make the Fit an easy recommendation.
    Chevrolet Sonic
    MSRP: $15,220 - $22,370
    EPA: 26 city/35 hwy
    Overview: The Sonic puts a bow tie on a handsome compact, featuring spirited styling along with responsive and agile handling.
    Hyundai Accent
    MSRP: $15,580 - $18,330
    EPA: 27 city/38 hwy
    Overview: No need for excuses here: the Accent, with its distinctive design and fuel-sipping engine, is a fine choice for an economical car.
    Kia Rio
    MSRP: $15,015 - $21,755
    EPA: 27 city/38 hwy
    Overview: The Rio is a perky, well-equipped and fuel-efficient sedan or five-door hatchback—and as a Kia, it’s a great value.
    Nissan Versa Note
    MSRP: $15,065 - $19,545
    EPA: 27 (Est) city/36 (Est) hwy
    Overview: Handsome styling, a roomy back seat, and the promise of astronomical fuel economy are not enough to make the Versa Note an appealing car.
    Toyota Yaris
    MSRP: $15,760 - $18,535
    EPA: 30 city/36 hwy
    Overview: A budget car that feels every bit of its low sticker price, the Yaris is an afterthought in a competitive segment.

